28/
The team will be monitoring the flow of funds and market sentiments to continuously adjust the APY or token inflation rate to ensure that they are in line with the prevailing monetary policy and keep token holders safe from excessive token inflation.

27/
This gives investors a way to have stable and predictable returns when staking their BLU tokens.

25/
We intend to keep the APY for staking high during the initial launch period to ensure that new investors can get access to our governance token at reasonable prices as we go through a period of ultra-high growth in the initial stage as words spread about the protocol.

24/
At Bluejay Finance, we see staking reward as a way to share the growth with the existing community. Our goal is to make the protocol governance accessible to the mass while maintaining the purchasing power of the governance token through periods of high and low growth.

22/
If a project attracts a high level of funds during its initial stage of launch and the inflation rate is kept low, the token price can hike excessively and crowd out new investors. https://t.co/WEyUqFvirD

18/
If the inflation rate exceeds the rate where new funds flow in, the price of the token falls. https://t.co/a6t5Ui5Fqw

17/
If funds flow in at a rate higher than the rate where new tokens are introduced, the price of the token increases. This is where the demand for the token (from people willing to swap assets like DAI for the governance token) exceeds the supply (from staking rewards). https://t.co/VlEMzSHpnn

16/
Using dark green blocks to represent new funds, we can see that if the rate of new funds equates to the inflation of the token supply, the price of the token remains the same. https://t.co/RgYauRTqtW

15/
Think of the token supply as the base of a container, the ‚ÄúAPY‚Äù as the rate the container is growing, and the flow of funds as a tap filling the container with more liquid. The height of the liquid determines the market price for the token.

14/
However, the model is not static because there is a flow of funds (from the sale of bonds) and there is continuous inflation of the token supply as existing tokens are staked for more tokens. https://t.co/dpHi254i1U

13/
If we look at the current supply of the token and the price of the token, we can get the current market cap of the protocol. This gives a vague estimation of how much the market thinks the protocol is worth currently. https://t.co/EikWwMstpu

10/
DeFi protocols benefit from the continuous stock split to allow early investors to sell their tokens when they feel richer and allow later-stage investors to buy in at reasonable prices.

8/
So rebase token protocols are really simply doing a continuous stock split.

So why do they do that?

5/
The APY in this case merely is the inflation rate of the governance tokens supply. 

In fact, having staking APY alone has no effect on the returns of your total investment.

4/
What you can be (somewhat) certain about is how the token in your wallet will grow. 

What you have (almost) no certainty about is how the price will change during this period of time.

3/ 
Eg.
Token price is 1/1000th: you lost half the value
Token price is 1/500th: your investment is worth exactly as much as it was
Token price is the same: you made a 500x return on the investment
Token price is doubled: you made a 1000x return on the investment

2/ When a product promises a 50,000% APY, it means you will get 500x the amount of tokens you stake at the end of 1 year. 

However, the actual return denominated in USD will vary largely depending on the price of the governance token in a year!

üßµ/ Staking APY is really just inflation rate

Used in Tradfi context APY allows your to compare products with different compounding schedules. 

However, Defi projects are quoting APY in the native token, introducing a new layer of complexity.
